# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: air-cooled-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In fluid dynamics, **drag**, sometimes referred to as **fluid resistance**, and also known as **viscous force**, is a force acting opposite to the direction of motion of any object moving with respect to a surrounding fluid.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] This can exist between two fluid layers, or between a fluid and a solid surface.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Drag forces tend to decrease fluid velocity relative to the solid object in the fluid's path.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Unlike other resistive forces, drag force depends on velocity.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Drag force is proportional to the relative velocity for low-speed flow and is proportional to the velocity squared for high-speed flow.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] This distinction between low and high-speed flow is measured by the Reynolds number.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] There are many distinct types of drag caused by different physical interactions between the object and fluid.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Last, in aerodynamics the term "parasitic drag" is often used.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Parasitic drag is the sum of form drag and skin friction drag and is entirely negative to an aircraft, in contrast with lift-induced drag which is a consequence of generating lift.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The effect of streamlining on the relative proportions of skin friction and form drag is shown in the table at right for an airfoil, which is a streamlined body, and a cylinder, which is a bluff body.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Also shown is a flat plate in two different orientations, illustrating the effect of orientation on the relative proportions of skin friction and form drag, and showing the pressure difference between front and back.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] A body is known as bluff or blunt when the source of drag is dominated by pressure forces, and streamlined if the drag is dominated by viscous forces.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] For example, road vehicles are bluff bodies.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] For aircraft, pressure and friction drag are included in the definition of parasitic drag.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Parasite drag is often expressed in terms of a hypothetical.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] With other parameters remaining the same, as the lift generated by a body increases, so does the lift-induced drag.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] This means that as the wing's angle of attack increases (up to a maximum called the stalling angle), the lift coefficient also increases, and so too does the lift-induced drag.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] At the onset of stall, lift is abruptly decreased, as is lift-induced drag, but viscous pressure drag, a component of parasite drag, increases due to the formation of turbulent unattached flow in the wake behind the body.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] For an aircraft at low speed, induced drag tends to be relatively greater than parasitic drag because a high angle of attack is required to maintain lift, increasing induced drag.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] As speed increases, the angle of attack is reduced and the induced drag decreases.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Parasitic drag, however, increases because the fluid is flowing more quickly around protruding objects increasing friction or drag.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] At even higher speeds (transonic), wave drag enters the picture.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Each of these forms of drag changes in proportion to the others based on speed.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The combined overall drag curve therefore shows a minimum at some airspeed - an aircraft flying at this speed will be at or close to its optimal efficiency.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Pilots will use this speed to maximize endurance (minimum fuel consumption), or maximize gliding range in the event of an engine failure.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The equivalent parasite area is the area which a flat plate perpendicular to the flow would have to match the parasite drag of an aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] It is a measure used when comparing the drag of different aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] For example, the Douglas DC-3 has an equivalent parasite area of 2.20 m2 (23.7 ft2) and the McDonnell Douglas DC-9, with 30 years of advancement in aircraft design, an area of 1.91 m2 (20.6 ft2) although it carried five times as many passengers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Drag depends on the properties of the fluid and on the size, shape, and speed of the object.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The graph to the right shows how $C_{\rm {D}}$ varies with $\mathrm {Re}$ for the case of a sphere.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Since the power needed to overcome the drag force is the product of the force times speed, the power needed to overcome drag will vary as the square of the speed at low Reynolds numbers, and as the cube of the speed at high numbers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] It can be demonstrated that drag force can be expressed as a function of a dimensionless number, which is dimensionally identical to the Bejan number.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Consequently, drag force and drag coefficient can be a function of Bejan number.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] As mentioned, the drag equation with a constant drag coefficient gives the force moving through a fluid at a relatively large velocity, i.e. high Reynolds number, Re > ~1000.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The reference area *A* is often the orthographic projection of the object, or the *frontal area,* on a plane perpendicular to the direction of motion.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] For objects with a simple shape, such as a sphere, this is the cross sectional area.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Sometimes a body is a composite of different parts, each with a different reference area (drag coefficient corresponding to each of those different areas must be determined).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In the case of a **wing**, the reference areas are the same, and the drag force is in the same ratio as the lift force.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Therefore, the reference for a wing is often the lifting area, sometimes referred to as "wing area" rather than the frontal area.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] For an object with a smooth surface, and non-fixed separation points (like a sphere or circular cylinder), the drag coefficient may vary with Reynolds number *Re*, up to extremely high values (*Re* of the order 107).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] For an object with well-defined fixed separation points, like a circular disk with its plane normal to the flow direction, the drag coefficient is constant for *Re* > 3,500.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The further the drag coefficient *Cd* is, in general, a function of the orientation of the flow with respect to the object (apart from symmetrical objects like a sphere).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] For example, a car cruising on a highway at 50 mph (80 km/h) may require only 10 horsepower (7.5 kW) to overcome aerodynamic drag, but that same car at 100 mph (160 km/h) requires 80 hp (60 kW).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] With a doubling of speeds, the drag/force quadruples per the formula.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Exerting 4 times the force over a fixed distance produces 4 times as much work.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] At twice the speed, the work (resulting in displacement over a fixed distance) is done twice as fast.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Since power is the rate of doing work, 4 times the work done in half the time requires 8 times the power.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Where $v_{w}$ is the wind speed and $v_{o}$ is the object speed (both relative to ground).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The hyperbolic cotangent also has a limit value of one, for large time *t*.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Velocity asymptotically tends to the terminal velocity *vt*, strictly from above *vt*.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] For objects of water-like density (raindrops, hail, live objects—mammals, birds, insects, etc.) falling in air near Earth's surface at sea level, the terminal velocity is roughly equal to $v_{t}=90{\sqrt {d}},\,$ with *d* in metres and *vt* in m/s.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Terminal velocity for very small objects (pollen, etc.) at low Reynolds numbers is determined by Stokes law.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In short, terminal velocity is higher for larger creatures, and thus potentially more deadly.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] A creature such as a mouse falling at its terminal velocity is much more likely to survive impact with the ground than a human falling at its terminal velocity.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The equation for **viscous resistance** or **linear drag** is appropriate for objects or particles moving through a fluid at relatively slow speeds (assuming there is no turbulence).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Purely laminar flow only exists up to Re = 0.1 under this definition.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In this case, the force of drag is approximately proportional to velocity.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The velocity asymptotically approaches the terminal velocity $v_{t}={\frac {(\rho -\rho _{0})Vg}{b}}$ .
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] For a given b , denser objects fall more quickly.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] For the special case of small spherical objects moving slowly through a viscous fluid (and thus at small Reynolds number), George Gabriel Stokes derived an expression for the drag constant: $b=6\pi \eta r\,$ where r is the Stokes radius of the particle, and $\eta$ is the fluid viscosity.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] For example, consider a small sphere with radius r = 0.5 micrometre (diameter = 1.0 μm) moving through water at a velocity v of 10 μm/s.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Using 10−3 Pa·s as the dynamic viscosity of water in SI units, we find a drag force of 0.09 pN.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] This is about the drag force that a bacterium experiences as it swims through water.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] For Reynolds numbers less than 1, Stokes' law applies and the drag coefficient approaches ${\frac {24}{Re}}$ .
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In aerodynamics, **aerodynamic drag**, also known as **air resistance**, is the fluid drag force that acts on any moving solid body in the direction of the air's freestream flow.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Alternatively, calculated from the flow field perspective (far-field approach), the drag force results from three natural phenomena: shock waves, vortex sheet, and viscosity.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] When the airplane produces lift, another drag component results.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Induced drag, symbolized $D_{i}$ , is due to a modification of the pressure distribution due to the trailing vortex system that accompanies the lift production.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] An alternative perspective on lift and drag is gained from considering the change of momentum of the airflow.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The wing intercepts the airflow and forces the flow to move downward.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] This results in an equal and opposite force acting upward on the wing which is the lift force.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The change of momentum of the airflow downward results in a reduction of the rearward momentum of the flow which is the result of a force acting forward on the airflow and applied by the wing to the air flow; an equal but opposite force acts on the wing rearward which is the induced drag.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Another drag component, namely wave drag, $D_{w}$ , results from shock waves in transonic and supersonic flight speeds.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The shock waves induce changes in the boundary layer and pressure distribution over the body surface.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Therefore, there are three ways of categorizing drag.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The pressure distribution acting on a body's surface *exerts* normal forces on the body.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Those forces can be added together and the component of that force that acts downstream represents the drag force, $D_{pr}$ .
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The nature of these normal forces combines shock wave effects, vortex system generation effects, and wake viscous mechanisms.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Viscosity of the fluid has a major effect on drag.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In the absence of viscosity, the pressure forces acting to hinder the vehicle are canceled by a pressure force further aft that acts to push the vehicle forward; this is called pressure recovery and the result is that the drag is zero.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] That is to say, the work the body does on the airflow is reversible and is recovered as there are no frictional effects to convert the flow energy into heat.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Pressure recovery acts even in the case of viscous flow.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Viscosity, however results in pressure drag and it is the dominant component of drag in the case of vehicles with regions of separated flow, in which the pressure recovery is infective.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The friction drag force, which is a tangential force on the aircraft surface, depends substantially on boundary layer configuration and viscosity.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The net friction drag, $D_{f}$ , is calculated as the downstream projection of the viscous forces evaluated over the body's surface.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The sum of friction drag and pressure (form) drag is called viscous drag.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] This drag component is due to viscosity.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The idea that a moving body passing through air or another fluid encounters resistance had been known since the time of Aristotle.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] According to Mervyn O'Gorman, this was named "drag" by Archibald Reith Low.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Louis Charles Breguet's paper of 1922 began efforts to reduce drag by streamlining.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Breguet went on to put his ideas into practice by designing several record-breaking aircraft in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Ludwig Prandtl's boundary layer theory in the 1920s provided the impetus to minimise skin friction.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] A further major call for streamlining was made by Sir Melvill Jones who provided the theoretical concepts to demonstrate emphatically the importance of streamlining in aircraft design.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In 1929 his paper 'The Streamline Airplane' presented to the Royal Aeronautical Society was seminal.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] He proposed an ideal aircraft that would have minimal drag which led to the concepts of a 'clean' monoplane and retractable undercarriage.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The aspect of Jones's paper that most shocked the designers of the time was his plot of the horse power required versus velocity, for an actual and an ideal plane.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] By looking at a data point for a given aircraft and extrapolating it horizontally to the ideal curve, the velocity gain for the same power can be seen.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] When Jones finished his presentation, a member of the audience described the results as being of the same level of importance as the Carnot cycle in thermodynamics.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The interaction of parasitic and induced drag *vs.* airspeed can be plotted as a characteristic curve, illustrated here.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In aviation, this is often referred to as the *power curve*, and is important to pilots because it shows that, below a certain airspeed, maintaining airspeed counterintuitively requires *more* thrust as speed decreases, rather than less.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The consequences of being "behind the curve" in flight are important and are taught as part of pilot training.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] At the subsonic airspeeds where the "U" shape of this curve is significant, wave drag has not yet become a factor, and so it is not shown in the curve.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Wave drag, sometimes referred to as compressibility drag, is drag that is created when a body moves in a compressible fluid and at the speed that is close to the speed of sound in that fluid.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In aerodynamics, wave drag consists of multiple components depending on the speed regime of the flight.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In transonic flight, wave drag is the result of the formation of shockwaves in the fluid, formed when local areas of supersonic (Mach number greater than 1.0) flow are created.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In practice, supersonic flow occurs on bodies traveling well below the speed of sound, as the local speed of air increases as it accelerates over the body to speeds above Mach 1.0.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] However, full supersonic flow over the vehicle will not develop until well past Mach 1.0.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Aircraft flying at transonic speed often incur wave drag through the normal course of operation.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In transonic flight, wave drag is commonly referred to as **transonic compressibility drag**.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Transonic compressibility drag increases significantly as the speed of flight increases towards Mach 1.0, dominating other forms of drag at those speeds.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In supersonic flight (Mach numbers greater than 1.0), **wave drag** is the result of shockwaves present in the fluid and attached to the body, typically **oblique shockwaves** formed at the leading and trailing edges of the body.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In highly supersonic flows, or in bodies with turning angles sufficiently large, **unattached shockwaves**, or **bow waves** will instead form.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Additionally, local areas of transonic flow behind the initial shockwave may occur at lower supersonic speeds, and can lead to the development of additional, smaller shockwaves present on the surfaces of other lifting bodies, similar to those found in transonic flows.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In supersonic flow regimes, **wave drag** is commonly separated into two components, **supersonic lift-dependent wave drag** and **supersonic volume-dependent wave drag**.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The closed form solution for the minimum wave drag of a body of revolution with a fixed length was found by Sears and Haack, and is known as the **Sears-Haack Distribution**.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Similarly, for a fixed volume, the shape for minimum wave drag is the **Von Karman Ogive**.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The Busemann biplane theoretical concept is not subject to wave drag when operated at its design speed, but is incapable of generating lift in this condition.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In 1752 d'Alembert proved that potential flow, the 18th century state-of-the-art inviscid flow theory amenable to mathematical solutions, resulted in the prediction of zero drag.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] This was in contradiction with experimental evidence, and became known as d'Alembert's paradox.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In the 19th century the Navier–Stokes equations for the description of viscous flow were developed by Saint-Venant, Navier, and Stokes.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Stokes derived the drag around a sphere at very low Reynolds numbers, the result of which is called Stokes' law.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] In the limit of high Reynolds numbers, the Navier–Stokes equations approach the inviscid Euler equations, of which the potential-flow solutions considered by d'Alembert are solutions.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] However, all experiments at high Reynolds numbers showed there is drag.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] Attempts to construct inviscid steady flow solutions to the Euler equations, other than the potential flow solutions, did not result in realistic results.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The notion of boundary layers—introduced by Prandtl in 1904, founded on both theory and experiments—explained the causes of drag at high Reynolds numbers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aerodynamic-drag] The boundary layer is the thin layer of fluid close to the object's boundary, where viscous effects remain important even when the viscosity is very small (or equivalently the Reynolds number is very large).
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Air-cooled engines are widely seen in applications where weight or simplicity is the primary goal.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity makes them suited for uses in small applications like chainsaws and lawn mowers, as well as small generators and similar roles.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] These qualities also make them highly suitable for aviation use, where they are widely used in general aviation aircraft and as auxiliary power units on larger aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity, in particular, also makes them common on motorcycles.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Most modern internal combustion engines are cooled by a closed circuit carrying liquid coolant through channels in the engine block and cylinder head.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] A fluid in these channels absorbs heat and then flows to a heat exchanger or radiator where the coolant releases heat into the air (or raw water, in the case of marine engines).
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Thus, while they are not *ultimately* cooled by the liquid, as the heat is exchanged with some other fluid like air, because of the liquid-coolant circuit they are known as *liquid-cooled*.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] In contrast, heat generated by an air-cooled engine is released directly into the air.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Typically this is facilitated with metal fins covering the outside of the cylinder head and cylinders which increase the surface area that air can act on.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Air may be force fed with the use of a fan and shroud to achieve efficient cooling with high volumes of air or simply by natural air flow with well designed and angled fins.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] In all combustion engines, a great percentage of the heat generated, around 44%, escapes through the exhaust.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Another 8% or so ends up in the oil, which itself has to be cooled in an oil cooler.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] This means less than half of the heat has to be removed through other systems.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] In an air-cooled engine, only about 12% of the heat flows out through the metal fins.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Air cooled engines usually run noisier, however it provides more simplicity which gives benefits when it comes to servicing and part replacement and is usually cheaper to be maintained.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Many motorcycles use air cooling for the sake of reducing weight and complexity.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Few current production automobiles have air-cooled engines (such as Tatra 815), but historically it was common for many high-volume vehicles.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] The orientation of the engine cylinders is commonly found in either single-cylinder or coupled in groups of two, and cylinders are commonly oriented in a horizontal fashion as a flat engine, while vertical straight-four engine have been used.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] During the 1920s and 30s there was a great debate in the aviation industry about the merits of air-cooled vs. liquid-cooled designs.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] At the beginning of this period, the liquid used for cooling was water at ambient pressure.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] The amount of heat carried away by a fluid is a function of its capacity and the difference in input and output temperatures.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] As the boiling point of water is reduced with lower pressure, and the water could not be efficiently pumped as steam, radiators had to have enough cooling power to account for the loss in cooling power as the aircraft climbed.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] The resulting radiators were quite large and caused a significant amount of aerodynamic drag.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] This placed the two designs roughly equal in terms of power to drag, but the air-cooled designs were almost always lighter and simpler.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] In 1921, the US Navy, largely due to the efforts of Commander Bruce G.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Leighton, decided that the simplicity of the air-cooled design would result in less maintenance workload, which was paramount given the limited working area of aircraft carriers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Leighton's efforts led to the Navy underwriting air-cooled engine development at Pratt & Whitney and Wright Aeronautical.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Most other groups, especially in Europe where aircraft performance was rapidly improving, were more concerned with the issue of drag.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] While air-cooled designs were common on light aircraft and trainers, as well as some transport aircraft and bombers, liquid-cooled designs remained much more common for fighters and high-performance bombers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] The drag issue was upset by the 1929 introduction of the NACA cowl, which greatly reduced the drag of air-cooled engines in spite of their larger frontal area, and the drag related to cooling was at this point largely even.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] This also led to development work attempting to eliminate the radiator entirely using evaporative cooling, allowing it to turn to steam and running the steam through tubes located just under the skin of the wings and fuselage, where the fast moving outside air condensed it back to water.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] While this concept was used on a number of record-setting aircraft in the late 1930s, it always proved impractical for production aircraft for a wide variety of reasons.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] In 1929, Curtiss began experiments replacing water with ethylene glycol in a Curtiss D-12 engine.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Ethylene glycol could run up to 250°C and reduced the radiator size by 50% compared to water-cooled designs.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] The experiments were extremely successful and by 1932 the company had switched all future designs to this coolant.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] At the time, Union Carbide held a monopoly on the industrial process to make ethylene glycol, so it was initially used only in the US, with Allison Engines picking it up soon after.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] It was not until the mid-1930s that Rolls-Royce adopted it as supplies improved, converting all of their engines to ethylene glycol.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] With the much smaller radiators and less fluid in the system, the weight and drag of these designs was well below contemporary air-cooled designs.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] On a weight basis, these liquid-cooled designs offered as much as 30% better performance.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] In the late- and post-war era, the high-performance field quickly moved to jet engines.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] This took away the primary market for late-model liquid-cooled engines.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Those roles that remained with piston power were mostly slower designs and civilian aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] In these roles, the simplicity and reduction in servicing needs is far more important than drag, and from the end of the war on almost all piston aviation engines have been air-cooled, with few exceptions.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] As of 2020, most of the engines manufactured by Lycoming and Continental are used by major manufacturers of light aircraft Cirrus, Cessna and so on.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Other engine manufactures using air-cooled engine technology are ULPower and Jabiru, more active in the Light-Sport Aircraft (LSA) and ultralight aircraft market.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Rotax uses a combination of air-cooled cylinders and liquid-cooled cylinder heads.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Some small diesel engines, e.g. those made by Deutz AG and Lister Petter are air-cooled.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Probably the only big Euro 5 truck air-cooled engine (V8 320 kW power 2100 N·m torque one) is being produced by Tatra.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] BOMAG part of the FAYAT group also utilizes an air cooled inline 6 cylinder motor, in many of their construction vehicles.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Stationary or portable engines were commercially introduced early in the 1900s.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] The first commercial production was by the New Way Motor Company of Lansing, Michigan, US.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] The company produced air-cooled engines in single and twin cylinders in both horizontal and vertical cylinder format.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Subsequent to their initial production which was exported worldwide, other companies took up the advantages of this cooling method, especially in small portable engines.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooled-engine] Applications include mowers, generators, outboard motors, pump sets, saw benches and auxiliary power plants and more.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:air-cooled-engine/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] An **aircraft carrier** is a warship designed to carry, launch, recover and support aircraft at sea, equipped with a full-length flight deck and hangar facilities that allow it to serve as a mobile, seagoing airbase.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Typically it is the capital ship of a fleet (known as a carrier battle group), as it allows a naval force to project seaborne air power far from national territory without depending on local airfields for the staging of aircraft operations.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] While heavier fixed-wing aircraft such as airlifters, gunships and bombers have been launched from aircraft carriers, these aircraft do not often land on a carrier due to flight deck limitations.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier, along with its onboard aircraft and defensive ancillary weapons, is the largest weapon system ever created.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] By their tactical prowess, mobility, autonomy and the variety of operational means, aircraft carriers are often the centerpiece of modern naval warfare, and have significant diplomatic influence in deterrence, command of the sea and air supremacy.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the Second World War, the aircraft carrier has replaced the battleship in the role of flagship of a fleet, and largely transformed naval battles from gunfire to beyond-visual-range air strikes.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies use several variants of the aircraft carrier, sometimes categorized as sub-types of aircraft carriers and sometimes as distinct types of aviation-capable ships.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft carriers may be classified according to the type of aircraft they carry and their operational assignments.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Navies have a variety of classification systems for their ships, and a definitive number of current aircraft carriers depends on the specific criteria.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] As of July 2026 there are 9 navies operating 24 active vessels designated by their respective navies as either an "Aircraft Carrier" or "Aircraft Cruiser".
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] These range in tonnage from the United States' 100,000 tonne USS *Gerald R.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford* to Brazil's 21,000 tonne NAM *Atlantico*.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of the types listed here are not strictly defined as aircraft carriers by some sources.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] A fleet carrier is intended to operate with the main fleet and usually provides an offensive capability.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] These are the largest carriers capable of fast speeds.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] By comparison, escort carriers were developed to provide defense for convoys of ships.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] They were smaller and slower with lower numbers of aircraft carried.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Most were built from mercantile hulls or, in the case of merchant aircraft carriers, were bulk cargo ships with a flight deck added on top.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Light aircraft carriers were fast enough to operate with the main fleet but of smaller size with reduced aircraft capacity.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Soviet aircraft carrier *Admiral Kusnetsov* was termed a "heavy aircraft-carrying cruiser".
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was primarily a legal construct to avoid the limitations of the Montreux Convention preventing 'aircraft carriers' transiting the Turkish Straits between the Soviet Black Sea bases and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] These ships, while sized in the range of large fleet carriers, were designed to deploy alone or with escorts.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition to supporting fighter aircraft and helicopters, they provide both strong defensive weaponry and heavy offensive missiles equivalent to a guided-missile cruiser.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The appellation "supercarrier" is not an official designation with any national navy, but a term used predominantly by the media and typically when reporting on larger and more advanced carrier types.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] It is also used when comparing carriers of various sizes and capabilities, both current and past.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] It was first used by *The New York Times* in 1938, in an article about the Royal Navy's HMS *Ark Royal*, that had a length of 800 feet (244 m), a displacement of 22,000 tons and was designed to carry 72 aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since then, aircraft carriers have consistently grown in size, both in length and displacement, as well as improved capabilities; in defense, sensors, electronic warfare, propulsion, range, launch and recovery systems, number and types of aircraft carried and number of sorties flown per day.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first aircraft carrier over 80,000 tonnes full-load displacement was the USS Forrestal launched in 1954.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] In total, the US Navy has had 5 different classes of aircraft carrier of this size definition, the Forrestal class, Kitty Hawk class, the Enterprise class, the Nimitz class and Gerald R Ford Class, two of which were conventional steam-powered and three nuclear-powered.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] USS *Enterprise*, launched in 1960, was the first carrier over 90,000 tonnes full load displacement and *Nimitz*, launched in 1972, was the first over 100,000 tonnes displacement.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] A total of 22 supercarriers have been launched by the US Navy since 1954, with 11 currently in service.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Both China (Type 003) and the United Kingdom (Queen Elizabeth class) have carriers in service with displacements from 80,000 to 85,000 tonnes and lengths from 280 to 320 meters (920 to 1,050 ft) which are described as "supercarriers".
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] France is also developing a new aircraft carrier (PANG) which is to have a full load displacement of 80,000 tonnes and will be considered a supercarrier.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The largest supercarrier in service as of 2024 is the US Navy's USS Gerald R.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford, with full load displacement of around 100,000 tons, length of 337 meters (1,106 ft) and capabilities that exceed those of any other class.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] A US Navy proposal for an aircraft carrier concept with a length of 1,310 feet and a displacement of 500,000 tons full load at a cost of $828 million in 1976 dollars.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Project Habakkuk could be considered an early proposal for an "ultracarrier".
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Several systems of identification symbol for aircraft carriers and related types of ship have been used.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] These include the pennant numbers used by the Royal Navy, Commonwealth countries, and Europe, along with the hull classification symbols used by the US and Canada.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Two months later, on 18 January 1911, Ely landed his Curtiss Pusher airplane on a platform on the armored cruiser USS *Pennsylvania* anchored in San Francisco Bay.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seaplane tender support ships came next, with the French *Foudre* of 1911.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Early in World War I, the Imperial Japanese Navy ship *Wakamiya* conducted the world's first carrier-launched air raid: on 6 September 1914, the *Wakamiya* used its crane to lower Farman seaplanes into the water.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Wakamiya* attacked the Austro-Hungarian cruiser SMS *Kaiserin Elisabeth* and the Imperial German gunboat *Jaguar* in Jiaozhou Bay off Qingdao; neither was hit.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first attack using an air-launched torpedo occurred on 2 August, when a torpedo was fired by Flight Commander Charles Edmonds from a Short Type 184 seaplane, launched from the seaplane carrier HMS *Ben-my-Chree*.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first carrier-launched airstrike was the Tondern raid in July 1918.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seven Sopwith Camels were launched from the battlecruiser HMS *Furious*, which had been completed as a carrier by replacing her planned forward turret with a flight deck and hangar prior to commissioning.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Camels attacked and damaged the German airbase at Tondern, Germany (modern day Tønder, Denmark), and destroyed two zeppelin airships.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first landing of an airplane on a moving ship was by Squadron Commander Edwin Harris Dunning, when he landed his Sopwith Pup on HMS *Furious* in Scapa Flow, Orkney, on 2 August 1917.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Landing on the forward flight deck required the pilot to approach round the ship's superstructure, a difficult and dangerous manoeuver, and Dunning was later killed when his airplane was thrown overboard while attempting another landing on *Furious*.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] HMS *Furious* was modified again when her rear turret was removed and another flight deck added over a second hangar for landing aircraft over the stern.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Her funnel and superstructure remained intact, however, and turbulence from the funnel and superstructure was severe enough that only three landing attempts were successful before further attempts were forbidden.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] This experience prompted the development of vessels with a flush deck and produced the first large fleet ships.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] In 1918, HMS *Argus* became the world's first carrier capable of launching and recovering naval aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] As a result of the Washington Naval Treaty of 1922, which limited the construction of new heavy surface combat ships, most early aircraft carriers were conversions of ships that were laid down (or had served) as different ship types: cargo ships, cruisers, battlecruisers, or battleships.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] These conversions gave rise to the USS *Langley* in 1922, the US *Lexington*-class aircraft carriers (1927), Japanese *Akagi* and *Kaga*, and British *Courageous* class (of which *Furious* was one).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Specialist carrier evolution was well underway, with several navies ordering and building warships that were purposefully designed to function as aircraft carriers by the mid-1920s.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] This resulted in the commissioning of ships such as the Japanese *Hōshō* (1922), HMS *Hermes* (1924, although laid down in 1918 before *Hōshō*), and *Béarn* (1927).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] During World War II, these ships would become known as fleet carriers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier dramatically changed naval warfare in World War II, because air power was becoming a significant factor in warfare.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The advent of aircraft as focal weapons was driven by the superior range, flexibility, and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] They had greater range and precision than naval guns, making them highly effective.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The versatility of the carrier was demonstrated in November 1940, when HMS *Illustrious* launched a long-range strike on the Italian fleet at their base in Taranto, signalling the beginning of the effective and highly mobile aircraft strikes.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] This operation in the shallow water harbor incapacitated three of the six anchored battleships at a cost of two torpedo bombers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] World War II in the Pacific Ocean involved clashes between aircraft carrier fleets.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Japanese surprise attack on the American Pacific fleet at Pearl Harbor naval and air bases on Sunday, 7 December 1941, was a clear illustration of the power projection capability afforded by a large force of modern carriers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Concentrating six carriers in a single unit turned naval history about, as no other nation had fielded anything comparable.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] In the "Doolittle Raid", on 18 April 1942, the US Navy carrier USS *Hornet* sailed to within 650 nautical miles (1,200 km) of Japan and launched 16 B-25 Mitchell medium bombers from her deck in a demonstrative retaliatory strike on the mainland, including the capital, Tokyo.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] However, the vulnerability of carriers compared to traditional capital ships was illustrated by the sinking of HMS *Glorious* by German battleships during the Norwegian campaign in 1940.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] This new-found importance of naval aviation forced nations to create a number of carriers, in efforts to provide air superiority cover for every major fleet to ward off enemy aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] This extensive usage led to the development and construction of 'light' carriers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Escort aircraft carriers, such as USS *Bogue*, were sometimes purpose-built but most were converted from merchant ships as a stop-gap measure to provide anti-submarine air support for convoys and amphibious invasions.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following this concept, light aircraft carriers built by the US, such as USS *Independence* (commissioned in 1943), represented a larger, more "militarized" version of the escort carrier.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although with similar complement to escort carriers, they had the advantage of speed from their converted cruiser hulls.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The UK 1942 Design Light Fleet Carrier was designed for building quickly by civilian shipyards and with an expected service life of about 3 years.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] They served the Royal Navy during the war, and the hull design was chosen for nearly all aircraft carrier equipped navies after the war, until the 1980s.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Emergencies also spurred the creation or conversion of highly unconventional aircraft carriers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] CAM ships were cargo-carrying merchant ships that could launch (but not retrieve) a single fighter aircraft from a catapult to defend the convoy from long range land-based German aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Noteworthy converted carriers were also USS *Sable* (IX-81) and USS *Wolverine* (IX-64) that both operated on the Great Lakes for training duties and were converted from paddle steamers, making them the only aircraft carriers with this type of propulsion.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before World War II, international naval treaties of 1922, 1930, and 1936 limited the size of capital ships, including carriers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since World War II, aircraft carrier designs have increased in size to accommodate a steady increase in aircraft size.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The large, modern *Nimitz* class of US Navy carriers has a displacement nearly four times that of the World War II–era USS *Enterprise*, yet its complement of aircraft is roughly the same—a consequence of the steadily increasing size and weight of individual military aircraft over the years.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Today's aircraft carriers are so expensive that some nations which operate them risk significant economic and military impact if a carrier is lost.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies that operate such aircraft carriers treat them as capital ships of fleets, a role previously held by the galleons, ships-of-the-line and battleships.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] This change took place during World War II in response to air power becoming a significant factor in warfare, driven by the superior range, flexibility and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following the war, carrier operations continued to increase in size and importance, and along with, carrier designs also increased in size and ability.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of these larger carriers, dubbed by the media as "supercarriers", displacing 75,000 tons or greater, have become the pinnacle of carrier development.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some are powered by nuclear reactors and form the core of a fleet designed to operate far from home.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Amphibious assault ships, such as the *Wasp* and *Mistral* classes, serve the purpose of carrying and landing Marines, and operate a large contingent of helicopters for that purpose.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Also known as "commando carriers" or "helicopter carriers", many have the capability to operate VSTOL aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The threatening role of aircraft carriers has a place in modern asymmetric warfare, like the gunboat diplomacy of the past.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers also facilitate quick and precise projections of overwhelming military power into such local and regional conflicts.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Lacking the firepower of other warships, carriers by themselves are considered vulnerable to attack by other ships, aircraft, submarines, or missiles.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The resulting group of ships is often termed a carrier strike group, battle group, carrier group, or carrier battle group.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] There is a view among some military pundits that modern anti-ship weapons systems, such as torpedoes and missiles, or even ballistic missiles with nuclear warheads have made aircraft carriers and carrier groups too vulnerable for modern combat.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers are large and long ships, although there is a high degree of variation depending on their intended role and aircraft complement.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The size of the carrier has varied over history and among navies, to cater to the various roles that global climates have demanded from naval aviation.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Regardless of size, the ship itself must house their complement of aircraft, with space for launching, storing, and maintaining them.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Space is also required for the large crew, supplies (food, munitions, fuel, engineering parts), and propulsion.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] US and French aircraft carriers are notable for having nuclear reactors powering their systems and propulsion.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The top of the carrier is the flight deck, where aircraft are launched and recovered.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the starboard side of this is the island, where ship navigation from the bridge and air traffic control from flyco are controlled and (in non-nuclear powered vessels), provides the location of the ship's funnel(s).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Queen Elizabeth*-class has two island structures; the forward island contains the navigation bridge, while the aft structure houses flyco.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The constraints of constructing a flight deck strongly affect the role of a given carrier, as they influence the weight, type, and configuration of the aircraft that may be launched.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, assisted launch mechanisms are used primarily for heavy aircraft, especially those loaded with air-to-ground weapons.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR is most commonly used on US Navy fleet carriers as it allows the deployment of heavy jets with full load-outs, especially on ground-attack missions.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] STOVL is used by other navies because it is cheaper to operate and still provides good deployment capability for fighter aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Due to the busy nature of the flight deck, only 20 or so aircraft may be on it at any one time.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] A hangar storage several decks below the flight deck is where most aircraft are kept, and aircraft are taken from the lower storage decks to the flight deck through the use of an elevator.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The hangar is usually quite large and can take up several decks of vertical space.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Munitions are commonly stored on the lower decks because they are highly explosive.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Usually this is below the waterline so that the area can be flooded in case of emergency.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] As "runways at sea", aircraft carriers have a flat-top flight deck, which launches and recovers aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft launch forward, into the wind, and are recovered from astern.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Creating such a surface at sea poses constraints on the carrier.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the size of the vessel is a fundamental limitation on runway length.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] This affects take-off procedure, as a shorter runway length of the deck requires that aircraft accelerate more quickly to gain lift.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] This either requires a thrust boost, a vertical component to its velocity, or a reduced take-off load (to lower mass).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The differing types of deck configuration, as above, influence the structure of the flight deck.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The form of launch assistance a carrier provides is strongly related to the types of aircraft embarked and the design of the carrier itself.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are two main philosophies to keep the deck short: add thrust to the aircraft, such as using a Catapult Assisted Take-Off (CATO-); and changing the direction of the airplanes' thrust, as in Vertical and/or Short Take-Off (V/STO-).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the recovery side of the flight deck, the adaptation to the aircraft load-out is mirrored.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Non-VTOL or conventional aircraft cannot decelerate on their own, and almost all carriers using them must have arrested-recovery systems (-BAR, e.g.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR or STOBAR) to recover their aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft that are landing extend a tailhook that catches on arrestor wires stretched across the deck to bring themselves to a stop in a short distance.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] If the aircraft are VTOL-capable or helicopters, they do not need to decelerate and hence there is no such need.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The arrested-recovery system has used an angled deck since the 1950s because, in case the aircraft does not catch the arresting wire, the short deck allows easier take off by reducing the number of objects between the aircraft and the end of the runway.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] It also has the advantage of separating the recovery operation area from the launch area.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Helicopters and aircraft capable of vertical or short take-off and landing (V/STOL) usually recover by coming abreast of the carrier on the port side and then using their hover capability to move over the flight deck and land vertically without the need for arresting gear.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers steam at speed, up to 35 knots (65 km/h; 40 mph) into the wind during flight deck operations to increase wind speed over the deck to a safe minimum.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] This increase in effective wind speed provides a higher launch airspeed for aircraft at the end of the catapult stroke or ski-jump, as well as making recovery safer by reducing the difference between the relative speeds of the aircraft and ship.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the early 1950s on conventional carriers it has been the practice to recover aircraft at an angle to port of the axial line of the ship.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The primary function of this angled deck is to allow aircraft that miss the arresting wires, referred to as a bolter, to become airborne again without the risk of hitting aircraft parked forward.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The angled deck allows the installation of one or two "waist" catapults in addition to the two bow cats.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] An angled deck also improves launch and recovery cycle flexibility with the option of simultaneous launching and recovery of aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Conventional ("tailhook") aircraft rely upon a landing signal officer (LSO, radio call sign 'paddles') to monitor the aircraft's approach, visually gauge glideslope, attitude, and airspeed, and transmit that data to the pilot.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before the angled deck emerged in the 1950s, LSOs used colored paddles to signal corrections to the pilot (hence the nickname).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] From the late 1950s onward, visual landing aids such as the optical landing system have provided information on proper glide slope, but LSOs still transmit voice calls to approaching pilots by radio.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Key personnel involved in the flight deck include the shooters, the handler, and the air boss.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Shooters are naval aviators or naval flight officers and are responsible for launching aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The handler works just inside the island from the flight deck and is responsible for the movement of aircraft before launching and after recovery.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The captain of the ship spends most of his time one level below primary on the Navigation Bridge.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Below this is the Flag Bridge, designated for the embarked admiral and his staff.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] To facilitate working on the flight deck of a US aircraft carrier, the sailors wear colored shirts that designate their responsibilities.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are at least seven different colors worn by flight deck personnel for modern United States Navy carrier air operations.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carrier operations of other nations use similar color schemes.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The superstructure of a carrier (such as the bridge, flight control tower) are concentrated in a relatively small area called an *island*, a feature pioneered on HMS *Hermes* in 1923.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] While the island is usually built on the starboard side of the flight deck, the Japanese aircraft carriers *Akagi* and *Hiryū* had their islands built on the port side.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Very few carriers have been designed or built without an island.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *flush deck* configuration proved to have significant drawbacks, primary of which was management of the exhaust from the power plant.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Fumes coming across the deck were a major issue in USS *Langley*.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition, lack of an island meant difficulties managing the flight deck, performing air traffic control, a lack of radar housing placements and problems with navigating and controlling the ship itself.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another deck structure that can be seen is a ski-jump ramp at the forward end of the flight deck.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was first developed to help launch short take off vertical landing (STOVL) aircraft take off at far higher weights than is possible with a vertical or rolling takeoff on flat decks.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Originally developed by the Royal Navy, it since has been adopted by many navies for smaller carriers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski-jump ramp works by converting some of the forward rolling movement of the aircraft into vertical velocity and is sometimes combined with the aiming of jet thrust partly downward.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] This allows heavily loaded and fueled aircraft a few more precious seconds to attain sufficient air velocity and lift to sustain normal flight.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Without a ski-jump, launching fully-loaded and fueled aircraft such as the Harrier would not be possible on a smaller flat deck ship before either stalling out or crashing directly into the sea.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although STOVL aircraft are capable of taking off vertically from a spot on the deck, using the ramp and a running start is far more fuel efficient and permits a heavier launch weight.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] As catapults are unnecessary, carriers with this arrangement reduce weight, complexity, and space needed for complex steam or electromagnetic launching equipment.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Vertical landing aircraft also remove the need for arresting cables and related hardware.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Russian, Chinese, and Indian carriers include a ski-jump ramp for launching lightly loaded conventional fighter aircraft but recover using traditional carrier arresting cables and a tailhook on their aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the Russian Sukhoi Su-33 is only able to launch from the carrier *Admiral Kuznetsov* with a minimal armament and fuel load.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another disadvantage is on mixed flight deck operations where helicopters are also present, such as on a US landing helicopter dock or landing helicopter assault amphibious assault ship.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski jump is not included as this would eliminate one or more helicopter landing areas; this flat deck limits the loading of Harriers but is somewhat mitigated by the longer rolling start provided by a long flight deck compared to many STOVL carriers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United States operates 11 nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carriers, with a total combined deck space over twice that of all other nations combined as of 2016.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] China operates one catapult-assisted aircraft carrier and two ski-jump carriers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United Kingdom and India each currently operate two ski-jump aircraft carriers, and France operates one nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carrier.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Russia deploys one ski-jump carrier, although it has not been operational since 2017.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the US operates nine large amphibious assault ships with the capability to launch vertical/short takeoff and landing (V/STOL) aircraft, and China operates four amphibious assault ships of a similar size as helicopter carriers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Italy operates two light V/STOL carriers, and both Spain and Iran operate one V/STOL aircraft-carrying assault ship.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Helicopter carriers are also operated by Japan (4, two converting to operate V/STOL fighters) France (3), Australia (2), Egypt (2), South Korea (2), Thailand (1), Brazil (1) and Iran (1).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Future aircraft carriers are under construction or planned by China, France, India, Italy, Russia, South Korea, and the US.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Royal Australian Navy operates two *Canberra*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two-ship class, based on the Spanish vessel *Juan Carlos I* and built by Navantia and BAE Systems Australia, represents the largest ships ever built for the Royal Australian Navy.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMAS *Canberra* underwent sea trials in late 2013 and was commissioned in 2014.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Her sister ship, HMAS *Adelaide*, was commissioned in December 2015.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Australian ships retain the ski-ramp from the *Juan Carlos I* design, although the RAN has not acquired carrier-based fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2017, the Brazilian Navy confirmed the purchase of HMS *Ocean* for (GBP) £84.6 million (equivalent to R$359.5M and US$113.2M) and renamed her *Atlântico*.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship was decommissioned from Royal Navy service in March 2018.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Brazilian Navy commissioned the carrier on 29 June 2018 in the United Kingdom.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] After undertaking a period of maintenance in the UK, the ship travelled to its new home port, Rio de Janeiro Navy Arsenal (AMRJ) to be fully operational by 2020.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Before leaving HMNB Devonport for her new homeport in Rio's AMRJ, *Atlântico* underwent operational sea training under the Royal Navy's Flag Officer Sea Training (FOST) program.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] China has had a long-term plan to operate six large aircraft carriers with two carriers per fleet.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is planning a class of eight LHD vessels, the Type 075 (NATO reporting name Yushen-class landing helicopter assault).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] This is a class of amphibious assault ship under construction by the Hudong–Zhonghua Shipbuilding company.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first ship was commissioned in April 2021.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is also planning a modified class of the same concept, the Type 076 landing helicopter dock, that will be equipped with an electromagnetic catapult system and will likely support launching unmanned combat aerial vehicles.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Egypt signed a contract with French shipbuilder DCNS to buy two *Mistral*-class helicopter carriers for approximately 950 million euros.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two ships were originally to be sold to Russia, but the deal was cancelled by France due to the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2014.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 2 June 2016, Egypt received the first of two helicopter carriers acquired in October 2015, the landing helicopter dock *Gamal Abdel Nasser*.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The flag transfer ceremony took place in the presence of Egyptian and French Navies' chiefs of staff, chairman and chief executive officers of both DCNS and STX France, and senior Egyptian and French officials.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 16 September 2016, DCNS delivered the second of two helicopter carriers, the landing helicopter dock *Anwar El Sadat* which also participated in a joint military exercise with the French Navy before arriving at her home port of Alexandria.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The French Navy operates the 42,000-tonne nuclear-powered aircraft carrier, *Charles de Gaulle*.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Commissioned in 2001, she is the flagship of the French Navy.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship carries a complement of Dassault Rafale M and E-2C Hawkeye aircraft, EC725 Caracal and AS532 Cougar helicopters for combat search and rescue, as well as modern electronics and Aster missiles.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] She is a CATOBAR-type carrier that uses two 75 m C13-3 steam catapults of a shorter version of the catapult system installed on the US *Nimitz*-class carriers, one catapult at the bow and one across the front of the landing area.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the French Navy operates three *Mistral*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] In October 2018, the French Ministry of Defence began an 18-month €40 million study for the replacement of the French aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* sometime after 2030.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, President Macron announced that construction of the next generation carrier would begin in around 2025 with sea trials to start in about 2036.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is planned to have a displacement of around 75,000 tons and to carry about 32 next-generation fighters, two to three E-2D Advanced Hawkeyes and a yet-to-be-determined number of unmanned carrier air vehicles.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has plans for a third carrier, INS *Vishal*, also known as *Indigenous Aircraft Carrier 2 (IAC-2)* with a displacement of over 65,000 tonnes and is planned with a CATOBAR system to launch and recover heavier aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has also issued a request for information (RFI) to procure four Landing helicopter dock displacing 30,000–40,000 tons with a capacity to operate 12 medium lift special ops and two heavy lift helicopters and troops for amphibious operations.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] On February 6, 2025, the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC) accepted the IRIS *Shahid Bagheri*, a 41,978-tonne drone UAV carrier converted from a container ship.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] was launched August 2013 and commissioned March 2015.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] the Japanese defense ministry's position is "We are not creating carrier air wings or carrier air squadrons" similar to the US Navy.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] from land bases; according to the 2020 Japanese Defense Ministry white paper the STOVL model was chosen for the JASDF due the lack of appropriately long runways to support air superiority capability across all of Japanese airspace.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] ships "for cooperation and advice on how to operate the fighter on the deck of the modified ships".
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] , marking 75 years since fixed-wing aircraft operated from a Japanese carrier.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Portuguese Navy plans, for the second half of 2026, to receive the NRP *D.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] João II*, a platform ship capable of operating aerial, surface and underwater drones, medium helicopters (Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk) and heavy helicopters (EH101 Merlin) helicopters of the Portuguese Air Force.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] One STOBAR carrier: *Admiral Flota Sovetskogo Soyuza Kuznetsov*: 55,000-tonne *Kuznetsov*-class STOBAR aircraft carrier.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Launched in 1985 as *Tbilisi*, renamed and operational from 1995.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Without catapults she can launch and recover lightly fueled naval fighters for air defense or anti-ship missions but not heavy conventional bombing strikes.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Officially designated an aircraft carrying cruiser, she is unique in carrying a heavy cruiser's complement of defensive weapons and large P-700 Granit offensive missiles.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The P-700 systems will be removed in the coming refit to enlarge her below decks aviation facilities as well as upgrading her defensive systems.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship has been out of service and in repairs since 2018.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The most recent projection stated that repairs would be completed and the ship transferred back to the Russian Navy sometime in 2024, however this projection has not been met as of July 2025, and no updates have been provided.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Russian government has been considering the potential replacement of *Admiral Kuznetsov* for some time and has considered the Shtorm-class aircraft carrier as a possible option.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] This carrier will be a hybrid of CATOBAR and STOBAR, given the fact that she uses both systems of launching aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is expected to cost between $1.8 billion and $5.63 billion.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2020, the project had not yet been approved and, given the financial costs, it was unclear whether it would be made a priority over other elements of Russian naval modernization.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] A class of 2 LHD, Project 23900 is planned and an official keel laying ceremony for the project happened on 20 July 2020.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two *Dokdo*-class 18,860-tonne full deck amphibious assault ships with hospital and well deck and facilities to serve as fleet flagships.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] South Korea had set tentative plans for procuring two light aircraft carriers by 2033, which would help make the ROKN a blue water navy.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, details of South Korea's planned carrier program (CVX) were finalized.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] A vessel of about 40,000 tons is envisaged carrying about 20 F-35B fighters as well as future maritime attack helicopters.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Service entry had been anticipated in the early 2030s.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] In 2025 the program was cancelled and replaced with a drone carrier program.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] One offshore helicopter support ship: HTMS *Chakri Naruebet* helicopter carrier: 11,400-tonne STOVL carrier based on Spanish *Príncipe de Asturias* design.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AV-8S Matador/Harrier STOVL fighter wing, mostly inoperable by 1999, was retired from service without replacement in 2006.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2010, the ship is used for helicopter operations and for disaster relief.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* is a 27,079-tonne amphibious assault ship (LHD) (outfitted as drone carrier) of the Turkish Navy that can be configured as a 24,660-tonne V/STOL aircraft carrier.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Construction began on 30 April 2016 by Sedef Shipbuilding Inc. at their Istanbul shipyard.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* was commissioned with a ceremony on 10 April 2023.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of a sister ship, to be named TCG *Trakya*, is currently being planned by the Turkish Navy.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Sikorsky S-70B Seahawk and the Bell AH-1 SuperCobra are the two main types of helicopters used on TCG *Anadolu*, with the occasional use of CH-47F Chinook helicopters of the Turkish Army during military exercises and operations.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AH-1W Super Cobras will eventually be complemented and replaced by the TAI T929 ATAK 2.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The jet-powered, low-observable drone Bayraktar MIUS Kızılelma and the MALE UAV Bayraktar TB3 are two UCAVs that are specifically designed and manufactured by Baykar Technologies to be used on TCG *Anadolu*.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The maiden flight of TAI Anka-3 (also part of Project MIUS), a jet-powered, flying wing type UCAV with stealth technology, was successfully completed on 28 December 2023.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 19 November 2024, Baykar Bayraktar TB3 UCAV successfully took-off from the flight deck of TCG *Anadolu* and landed on the ship.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] It was the first time a fixed-wing unmanned aircraft of this size and class had successfully landed on a short-runway landing helicopter dock, without the use of an arresting gear.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 3 January 2024, the Turkish government approved the plan for the design and construction of a larger aircraft carrier, named the *MUGEM*-class.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 15 February 2024, the Design and Projects Office of the Turkish Navy announced that it will be a STOBAR aircraft carrier with an overall length of 285 metres (935 ft), beam of 72 metres (236 ft), draught of 10.1 metres (33 ft), and displacement of 60,000 tons.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is to have a combined diesel–electric and gas (CODLAG) propulsion system and a maximum speed of more than 25 knots (29 mph; 46 km/h).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of the first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier began on 2 January 2025.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier is being built at the Istanbul Naval Shipyard.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two 80,600-tonne (est. full load) *Queen Elizabeth*-class STOVL carriers which operate the F-35 Lightning II.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMS *Queen Elizabeth* was commissioned in December 2017 and HMS *Prince of Wales* in December 2019.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The current US fleet of *Nimitz*-class carriers will be followed into service (and in some cases replaced) by the *Gerald R.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is expected that the ships will be more automated in an effort to reduce the amount of funding required to maintain and operate the vessels.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The main new features are implementation of Electromagnetic Aircraft Launch System (EMALS) (which replaces the old steam catapults) and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] In terms of future carrier developments, Congress has discussed the possibility of accelerating the phasing-out of one or more *Nimitz*-class carriers, postponing or canceling the procurement of CVN-81 and CVN-82, or modifying the purchase contract.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Following the deactivation of USS *Enterprise* in December 2012, the US fleet comprised 10 fleet carriers, but that number increased back to 11 with the commissioning of *Gerald R.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The House Armed Services Seapower subcommittee on 24 July 2007, recommended seven or eight new carriers (one every four years).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] However, the debate has deepened over budgeting for the $12–14.5 billion (plus $12 billion for development and research) for the 100,000-tonne *Gerald R.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Ford*-class carrier (estimated service 2017) compared to the smaller $2 billion 45,000-tonne *America*-class amphibious assault ships, which are able to deploy squadrons of F-35Bs.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first of this class, USS *America*, is now in active service with another, USS *Tripoli*, and 9 more are planned.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] In a report to Congress in February 2018, the Navy stated it intends to maintain a "12 CVN force" as part of its 30-year acquisition plan.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] A few aircraft carriers have been preserved as museum ships.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently portrayed in a number of Hollywood films including *Midway* (2019) and the carrier USS *Nimitz* is centrally featured in the science fiction film *The Final Countdown* (1980).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The original film version about the Battle at Midway was made in England and titled *Midway* (1976).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently featured in both *Top Gun* and *Top Gun: Maverick* as providing the launch sites and mission operations support for the fighter operations seen in both films.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Japanese aircraft carriers involved in the attack on Pearl Harbor are featured in the 1970 film *Tora!
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] Tora!* as well as the more recent film from 2001 *Pearl Harbor*.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier USS *Ronald Reagan* makes a cameo appearance at the end of the 2012 science fiction film *Battleship*.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] In the 2025 film *Mission: Impossible – The Final Reckoning*, the aircraft carrier USS *George Bush* is featured as delivering its special agent to a submarine rendezvous with the nuclear-powered USS *Ohio* in the Bering Straits by Alaska.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-carrier-p02] The 50-minute documentary titled *City of Steel: Carrier* was released by the Discovery Channel in 2000 covering the final months of building and inspecting the USS *Harry Truman* through its commissioning by President Bill Clinton.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-controls] *Right* - The left magneto p-lead is grounded, and the right is open.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the left magneto and enables the right magneto only.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-controls] *Left* - The right magneto p-lead is grounded, and the left is open.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the right magneto and enables the left magneto only.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-controls] *Both* - This is the normal operating configuration, both p-leads are open, enabling both magnetos.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-controls] *Start* - The pinion gear on the starter motor is engaged with the flywheel and the starter motor runs to turn the engine over.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-controls] In most cases, only the left magneto is active (the right p-lead is grounded) due to timing differences between the magnetos at low RPMs.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-controls] In an aircraft with a **fixed-pitch propeller**, there is no direct control over the propeller rotational speed, which depends on the airspeed and loading.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-controls] Therefore, the pilot has to pay attention to the RPM indicator and adjust the throttle/power lever in order to maintain the desired constant speed of the propeller.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-controls] For example, when the airspeed reduces and the loading increases (e.g., in a climb), RPM will decrease and the pilot has to increase the throttle/power.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-controls] When the airspeed increases and the loading decreases (e.g., in a dive), the RPM will increase and the pilot has to decrease the throttle/power in order to prevent RPM from exceeding the operational limits and damaging the motor.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-controls] Restricting the volume of cooling airflow too much.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-controls] Insufficient delivery of lubricating oil to the engine's moving parts.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Many variations of **aircraft engine starting** have been used since the Wright brothers made their first powered flight in 1903.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] The methods used have been designed for weight saving, simplicity of operation and reliability.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Early piston engines were started by hand.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Geared hand starting, electrical and cartridge-operated systems for larger engines were developed between the First and Second World Wars.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Gas turbine aircraft engines such as turbojets, turboshafts and turbofans often use air/pneumatic starting, with the use of *bleed air* from built-in auxiliary power units (APUs) or external air compressors now seen as a common starting method.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Often only one engine needs be started using the APU (or remote compressor).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] After the first engine is started using APU bleed air, *cross-bleed air* from the running engine can be used to start the remaining engine(s).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Hand starting of aircraft piston engines by swinging the propeller is the oldest and simplest method, the absence of any onboard starting system giving an appreciable weight saving.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Positioning of the propeller relative to the crankshaft is arranged such that the engine pistons pass through top dead centre during the swinging stroke.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] As the ignition system is normally arranged to produce sparks before top dead centre there is a risk of the engine kicking back during hand starting.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] To avoid this problem one of the two magnetos used in a typical aero engine ignition system is fitted with an 'impulse coupling', a spring-loaded device which delays the spark until top dead centre and which also increases the rotational speed of the magneto to produce a stronger spark.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] When the engine fires, the impulse coupling no longer operates and the second magneto is switched on.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Note that this is different from the manual "turning over" of a radial piston engine, which is done to release oil that has become trapped in the lower cylinders prior to starting to avoid engine damage.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] The two appear similar, but while hand starting involves a sharp, strong "yank" on the prop to start the engine, turning over is simply done by turning the prop through a certain set amount.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Accidents have occurred during lone pilot hand starting, whether due to high throttle settings, brakes not having been applied, or wheel chocks not being used, all resulting in the aircraft moving off without the pilot at the controls.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] The Hucks starter (invented by Bentfield Hucks during WWI) is a mechanical replacement for the ground crew.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Based on a vehicle chassis the device uses a clutch driven shaft to turn the propeller, disengaging as the engine starts.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] A Hucks starter is used regularly at the Shuttleworth Collection for starting period aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Self-sustaining motor gliders (often known as 'turbos') are fitted with small two-stroke engines with no starting system, for ground testing a cord is wrapped around the propeller boss and pulled rapidly in conjunction with operating decompressor valves.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] These engines are started in flight by operating the decompressor and increasing airspeed to windmill the propeller.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Early variants of the Slingsby Falke motor glider use a cockpit mounted pull start system.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Aircraft began to be equipped with electrical systems around 1930, powered by a battery and small wind-driven generator.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] The systems were initially not powerful enough to drive starter motors.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Introduction of engine-driven generators solved the problem.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Introduction of electric starter motors for aero engines increased convenience at the expense of extra weight and complexity.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] They were a necessity for flying boats with high mounted, inaccessible engines.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Powered by an onboard battery, ground electrical supply or both, the starter is operated by a key or switch in the cockpit.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] The key system usually facilitates switching of the magnetos.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] In cold ambient conditions the friction caused by viscous engine oil causes a high load on the starting system.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Another problem is the reluctance of the fuel to vaporise and combust at low temperatures.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Oil dilution systems were developed (mixing fuel with the engine oil), and engine pre-heaters were used (including lighting fires under the engine).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] The Ki-Gass priming pump system was used to assist starting of British engines.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Aircraft fitted with variable-pitch propellers or constant speed propellers are started in fine pitch to reduce air loads and current in the starter motor circuit.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Many light aircraft are fitted with a 'starter engaged' warning light in the cockpit, a mandatory airworthiness requirement to guard against the risk of the starter motor failing to disengage from the engine.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] The Coffman starter was an explosive cartridge operated device, the burning gases either operating directly in the cylinders to rotate the engine or operating through a geared drive.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] First introduced on the Junkers Jumo 205 diesel engine in 1936 the Coffman starter was not widely used by civil operators due to the expense of the cartridges.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] In 1920 Roy Fedden designed a piston engine gas starting system, used on the Bristol Jupiter engine in 1922.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] A system used in early Rolls-Royce Kestrel engines ducted high-pressure air from a ground unit through a camshaft driven distributor to the cylinders via non-return valves, the system had disadvantages only overcome by conversion to electric starting.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] When a piston engine needs to be started in flight the electric starter motor can be used.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] This is a normal procedure for motor gliders that have been soaring with the engine turned off.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] During aerobatics with earlier aircraft types it was not uncommon for the engine to cut during manoeuvres due to carburettor design.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] With no electric starter installed, engines can be restarted by diving the aircraft to increase airspeed and the rotation speed of the 'windmilling' propeller.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] An aero engine inertia starter uses a pre-rotated flywheel to transfer kinetic energy to the crankshaft, normally through reduction gears and a clutch to prevent over-torque conditions.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Three variations have been used, hand driven, electrically driven and a combination of both.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] When the flywheel is fully energised either a manual cable is pulled or a solenoid is used to engage the starter.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Starting of a gas turbine engine requires rotation of the compressor to a speed that provides sufficient pressurised air to the combustion chambers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] The starting system has to overcome inertia of the compressor and friction loads, the system remains in operation after combustion starts and is disengaged once the engine has reached self-idling speed.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Two types of electrical starter motor can be used, direct-cranking (to disengage as internal combustion engines) and starter-generator system (permanently engaged).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Small gas turbine engines, particularly turboshaft engines used in helicopters and cruise missile turbojets can be started by a geared hydraulic motor using oil pressure from a ground supply.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] With air-start systems, gas turbine engine compressor spools are rotated by the action of a large volume of compressed air acting directly on the compressor blades or driving the engine through a small, geared turbine motor.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] These motors can weigh up to 75% less than an equivalent electrical system.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] The compressed air can be supplied from an on-board auxiliary power unit (APU), a portable gas generator used by ground crew or by cross feeding bleed air from a running engine in the case of multi-engined aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] The Turbomeca Palouste gas generator was used to start the Spey engines of the Blackburn Buccaneer.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] The de Havilland Sea Vixen was equipped with its own Palouste in a removable underwing container to facilitate starting when away from base.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Other military aircraft types using ground supplied compressed air for starting include the Lockheed F-104 Starfighter and variants of the F-4 Phantom using the General Electric J79 turbojet engine.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Versions of the Rolls-Royce Avon turbojet engine used a geared turbine starter motor that burned isopropyl nitrate as the fuel.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] In military service this monofuel had the NATO designation of S-746 AVPIN.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] For starting a measured amount of fuel was introduced to the starter combustion chamber then ignited electrically, the hot gases spinning the turbine at high revolutions with the exhaust exiting overboard.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Similar in operating principle to the piston engine Coffman starter, an explosive cartridge drives a small turbine engine which is connected by gears to the compressor shaft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Developed for short-haul airliners, most civil and military aircraft requiring self-contained starting systems these units are known by various names including Auxiliary Power Unit (APU), Jet Fuel Starter (JFS), Air Start Unit (ASU) or Gas Turbine Compressor (GTC).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Comprising a small gas turbine which is electrically started, these devices provide compressed bleed air for engine starting and often also provide electrical and hydraulic power for ground operations without the need to run the main engines.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Two small petrol/oil mix tanks were fitted in the annular intake.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] The Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird used two Buick Nailheads as starter motors, which were mounted on an AG-330 Start Kart trolley, later with Chevrolet big-block 454-cubic-inch (7.44 L) V8 engines.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Gas turbine engines can be shut down in flight, intentionally by the crew to save fuel or during a flight test or unintentionally due to fuel starvation or flameout after a compressor stall.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Sufficient airspeed is used to 'windmill' the compressor then fuel and ignition are switched on, an on-board auxiliary power unit may be used at high altitudes where the air density is lower.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] During zoom climb operations of the Lockheed NF-104A the jet engine was shut down on climbing through 85,000 ft (26,000 m) and was started using the windmill method on descent through denser air.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Pulse jet engines are uncommon aircraft powerplants.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] However, the Argus As 014 used to power the V-1 flying bomb and Fieseler Fi 103R Reichenberg was a notable exception.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Once the engine started and the temperature rose to the minimum operating level, the external air hose and connectors were removed, and the resonant design of the tailpipe kept the pulse jet firing.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] Each cycle or pulse of the engine began with the shutters open; fuel was injected behind them and ignited, and the resulting expansion of gases forced the shutters closed.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] As the pressure in the engine dropped following combustion, the shutters reopened and the cycle was repeated, roughly 40 to 45 times per second.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine-starting] The electrical ignition system was used only to start the engine; heating of the tailpipe skin maintained combustion.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] An **aircraft fuel system** allows the crew to pump, manage, and deliver aviation fuel to the propulsion system and auxiliary power unit (APU) of an aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Fuel systems differ greatly due to different performance of the aircraft in which they are installed.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] A single-engine piston aircraft has a simple fuel system, while a tanker (such as the KC-135) not only manages its own fuel but can also provide fuel to other aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Fuel is piped through fuel lines to a fuel control valve (usually known as the fuel selector).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] The first function is to act as a fuel shut-off valve.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] This is required to provide the crew with a means to prevent fuel reaching the engine in case of an engine fire.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] The second function is to allow the pilot to choose which tank feeds the engine.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Many aircraft have the left tank and right tank selections available to the pilot.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Some Cessna airplanes feed only from both tanks; and many have the option to feed from left, right, or both tanks.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] The reason to have left only and right only options is to allow pilots to balance fuel load to reduce the banking moment.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] In some aircraft, the shut-off function is a different valve located after the fuel selector valve.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Typically, after the selector valve—situated at a low point in the fuel run—there is a gascolator — a fuel filter that can be opened on the ground and drained of fuel impurities denser than petroleum, mainly water and sediment.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Other drainage points are in each tank (often more than one contaminant collection sump per tank) and at the injection pump.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Each tank is vented (or pressurised) to allow air into the tank to take the place of burned fuel; otherwise, the tank would be in negative pressure which would result in engine fuel starvation.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] A vent also allows for changes in atmospheric pressure and temperature.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] The fuel level indication system in the simplest form is a transparent window on the tank side and in its usual application a float-driven potentiometer installed in the tank.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] After the TWA Flight 800 disaster, a revision was made to aircraft fuel systems to address the potential explosion hazard of electrical components located in the fuel tank.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Single-engine piston aircraft fuel level systems moved to utilize float level gauges from the CNG and LPG industries which had the float drive a magnetic coupling and relocated the potentiometer outside the fuel tank.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Some single-engine aircraft use capacitive probes in the fuel tanks.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] As fuel is burned, more air enters the tank and the capacitance decreases; this is read by a computer and the fuel amount is calculated and displayed to the pilots.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Recent advances in magnetoresistive technology have evolved new fuel level sensors for general aviation applications.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] This system is not affected by any additive or fuel combination to replace 100LL for piston-powered aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Single-engine light aircraft fuel tanks are usually in the wings, but some aircraft have a small "header tank" between the normal fuel tank and the engine, to facilitate reliable fuel flow to the engine.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] On many small or very old single-engine aircraft, header tanks (and even main tanks) are often mounted above and/or immediately behind the engine.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] A few (particularly ultralight aircraft) have them in the fuselage or on the airframe behind the pilot and/or passenger(s).
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Adding tanks and engines increases the complexity of the fuel system and its management.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] All of the considerations made for the twin piston are applicable to turbine fuel systems.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Additional consideration apply because of the higher altitudes, different fuel, lower temperatures, and longer flights.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] To avoid water condensation or the fuel itself solidifying at low temperatures (−55 °C), fuel tanks have thermometers and heating systems.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Many are pressurized with engine bleed air to keep moist air out and ensure positive pressure feed to the pumps.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] In larger aircraft, fuel tanks also are in the fuselage and their load affects the center of gravity of the aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] This imposes limitations on the amount of fuel carried and the order in which fuel must be used.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Turbine engines burn fuel faster than reciprocating engines do.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Because fuel needs to be injected in to a combustor, the injection system of a turbine aircraft must provide fuel at higher pressure and flow compared to that for a piston engine aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] The refueling system of larger aircraft includes a single positive pressure refueling point from which all tanks can be fueled.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] How much and to which tanks fuel is fed during refueling operations is determined by the controls in the refueling panel, usually installed nearby and accessible to ground crews.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] External tanks are used to extend the range of an aircraft.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] Drop tanks are used by combat aircraft that need to discard them after use for performance reasons.
[src:air-cooled-engine/aircraft-fuel-system] A fuel pump is required to transfer fuel from a tip tank to a main tank.
